{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Hope and Other Dangerous Pursuits | title_orig = | translator = | image = Lalamibook.jpg | author = [[Laila Lalami]] | cover_artist = | country = [[Morocco]] | language = English | series = | genre = Novel | publisher = [[Algonquin Books]] | release_date = October 7, 2005 | media_type = Print (hardback & paperback) | pages = | isbn = 1-56512-493-6 | isbn_note = (hardback edition) | dewey= 813/.6 22 | congress= PS3612.A543 H68 2005 | oclc= 59881995 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Hope and Other Dangerous Pursuits''''' is a 2005 novel by [[Morocco|Moroccan]] American author [[Laila Lalami]]. First published in the United States, it offers a wider view of the immigration phenomenon from North Africa to Europe. The novel was inspired by a story that Lalami read in ''[[Le Monde]]''.<ref name = Marchi/>
==Plot summary==
A group of young Moroccan immigrants seeking a better life in Spain cross the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] on a lifeboat. When it capsizes near shore, it is everyone for themselves. The book then chronicles the lives of four of the passengers, Murad, Halima, Aziz and Faten, exploring their lives before the trip and what motivated their attempt at immigration.
==Themes== The novel sets up an empathy for the situations which create the need for migration; as critic Lisa Marchi points out, the novel "highlights the economic precarity, social invisibility, and indisputable vulnerability of the migrants".<ref name = Marchi>{{Cite journal| issn = 1528-4212| volume = 51| issue = 4| pages = 603–626| last = Marchi| first = Lisa| title = Ghosts, Guests, Hosts: Rethinking "Illegal" Migration and Hospitality Through Arab Diasporic Literature| journal = Comparative Literature Studies| date = 2014| url = https://muse.jhu.edu/journals/comparative_literature_studies/v051/51.4.marchi.html}}</ref>
The novel also complicates the nature of the "Muslim" identity of many of these immigrants.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Plotting Against America: 9/11 and the Spectacle of Terror in Contemporary American Fiction |first=Catherine |last=Morley |pages=294–312 |url=http://www.enl.auth.gr/gramma/gramma08/morley.pdf |journal=Gramma/Γράμμα: Journal of Theory and Criticism |volume=08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616033408/http://www.enl.auth.gr/gramma/gramma08/morley.pdf |archivedate=2015-06-16 |df= }}</ref>
==Reception== When describing the novel, critic Lisa Marchi said it's "wisely constructed: the writer confidently travels between temporal settings and geographical zones to gradually unveil the genealogy of each character’s migratory project".<ref name = Marchi/>
