{{Infobox holiday | holiday_name = Maghi | image = Gurudwara Muktsar Sahib.jpg | type = Sikh |observedby = Sikhs |longtype = religious and cultural | begins = 1st [[Magh (Sikh calendar)|Magh]] [[Sankranti|Sangrand]] [[Punjabi calendar]] | date2017 = Saturday, 14 January | date2018 = Sunday, 14 January | date2019 = Tuesday, 15 January | celebrations = Ritual bathing, eat traditional food |relatedto = [[Makar Sankranti]] | frequency = annual |significance = Midwinter festival, celebration of [[Winter Solstice]] }}
'''Maghi''' is the annual festival and one of the seasonal gathering of the [[Sikh]]s.<ref name=melton1769>{{cite book|author1=J. Gordon Melton|author2=Martin Baumann|title=Religions of the World: A Comprehensive Encyclopedia of Beliefs and Practices, 2nd Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v2yiyLLOj88C&pg=PA1769 |year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-204-3|page=1769}}</ref> It is celebrated at Muktsar in the memory of forty Sikh martyrs (''Chalis Mukte''), who once had deserted the tenth and last human Guru of [[Sikhism]], [[Guru Gobind Singh]] at Anandpur Sahib, but later rejoined the Guru and died while fighting the [[Mughal Empire]] army led by Wazir Khan in 1705.<ref name=melton1769/> Sikhs make a pilgrimage to the site of this Sikh-Muslim war, and take a dip in the sacred water tanks of Muktsar.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/devotees-take-holy-dip-115011400698_1.html Business Standard 14 January 2015]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Dh6jydKXikoC&pg=PA695&dq=muktsar+battle&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjboL63h8LRAhVGnBoKHSorB-4Q6AEIHzAB#v=onepage&q=muktsar%20battle&f=false] Tony Jaques (2007) Dictionary of Battles and Sieges: F-O. Greenwood Publishing Co.</ref>
A fair (''mela'') is held at Muktsar Sahib every year and called the [[Mela Maghi]] is held in memory of the forty Sikh martyrs.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xajcAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|title=Historical Dictionary of Sikhism|page=65|author=Fenech, E. Louis |author2=Mcleod, H. W.|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-3601-1}}</ref> Before this tradition started to commemorate the Sikh martyrs who gave their lives to protect the tenth Guru, the festival was observed and mentioned by [[Guru Amar Das]], the third Guru of Sikhism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DQeKTUXphPMC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=guru%20amar%20das%20maghi&source=bl&ots=8oz32_P9qt&sig=nic2zdYZVYxSEAkPtnzg1EM5P3M&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ki9OVKPtC8ze7AaHwoCoDw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=guru%20amar%20das%20maghi&f=false|title=Glimpses of Sikhism|first=Major Nahar Singh|last=Jawandha|date=1 January 2010|publisher=Sanbun Publishers|accessdate=14 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>
[[Makar Sankranti]] celebrated in other parts of Indian subcontinent by Hindus, is known as Maghi in Punjab<ref name="autogenerated2"/> and is always on the first day of the month of [[Magha (month)|Magha]] in [[Bikrami calendar]]. On Maghi, when the sun takes its northern journey on entering the sign of Makara or Capricorn, the Hindus take bath in the Ganges or if that is not possible, in some other river, rivulet, canal or pond.<ref name="autogenerated2">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1O0eAQAAMAAJ&dq=maghi+punjab+bathing+rivers&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=ganges Census of India, 1961: Punjab. Managher of Publications]</ref> It follows the festival of [[Lohri]] in north India, particularly popular in the [[Punjab region]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Dr. H.S. Singha|title=Sikh Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRodBu9seiIC&pg=PA101|year=2005|publisher=Hemkunt Press|isbn=978-81-7010-245-8|pages=101–102}}</ref>
Maghi is celebrated by people eating [[kheer]] such as Rauh di kheer which is an old dish where rice is cooked in sugarcane juice. The dish is prepared in the evening before Maghi and is kept to cool. It is served cold next morning on Maghi with red-chilly mixed curd.<ref>'Rauh di kheer’ is the people’s favourite. The Tribune. (14.01.2017 )accessed 15.01.2017 [http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/amritsar/-rauh-di-kheer-is-the-people-s-favourite/350132.html]</ref> In some parts of [[Punjab, India]], it is also traditional to eat [[kichdi]] mixed with lentils, consume raw sugarcane and [[jaggery]],<ref name="autogenerated1">Sundar mundarye ho by Assa Singh Ghuman Waris Shah Foundation ISBN B1-7856-043-7</ref> Fairs are held at many places on Maghi.<ref>Sekhon, Iqbal S. The Punjabis. 2. Religion, society and culture of the Punjabis. Cosmos (2000) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bU0wAQAAIAAJ&q=maghi+makar+sankranti+punjab&dq=maghi+makar+sankranti+punjab&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqzKzu9rjTAhVSKlAKHYKQCFU4ChDoAQghMAA]</ref>
